ğŸ”¹ What is a List in Python?
A list is a collection used to store multiple items in a single variable.
ğŸ‘‰ Lists are:
Ordered (items have index positions)
Changeable (mutable)
Allow duplicate values

ğŸ”¹ How to Create a List
servers = ["web", "db", "cache"]
print(servers)

ğŸ”¹ Access List Items (Indexing)
Index starts from 0
servers = ["web", "db", "cache"]

print(servers[0])   # web
print(servers[1])   # db
print(servers[-1])  # cache (last item)

ğŸ”¹ Change List Items
servers = ["web", "db", "cache"]
servers[1] = "database"
print(servers)

ğŸ”¹ Add Items to a List
1ï¸âƒ£ append() â€“ add at end
servers = ["web", "db"]
servers.append("cache")
print(servers)

2ï¸âƒ£ insert() â€“ add at specific position
servers.insert(1, "loadbalancer")
print(servers)

ğŸ”¹ Remove Items from a List
1ï¸âƒ£ remove() â€“ remove by value
servers.remove("db")

2ï¸âƒ£ pop() â€“ remove by index
servers.pop(0)   # removes "web"
3ï¸âƒ£ del
del servers[1]

ğŸ”¹ List Length
servers = ["web", "db", "cache"]
print(len(servers))

ğŸ”¹ Loop Through a List
for loop
servers = ["web", "db", "cache"]
for server in servers:
    print(server)
with index
for i in range(len(servers)):
    print(i, servers[i])

ğŸ”¹ Check Item Exists in List
if "db" in servers:
    print("Database server exists")

ğŸ”¹ List Slicing
servers = ["web", "db", "cache", "lb"]
print(servers[0:2])   # ['web', 'db']
print(servers[:3])    # first 3 items
print(servers[1:])    # from index 1 to end

ğŸ”¹ Common List Methods (Important)
nums = [5, 2, 9, 1]
nums.sort()        # sort list
nums.reverse()     # reverse list
nums.clear()       # remove all items

ğŸ”¹ List with Mixed Data Types
info = ["web", 80, True, 10.5]
print(info)

ğŸ”¹ Nested List (List inside List)
servers = [
    ["web", "192.168.1.10"],
    ["db", "192.168.1.20"]
]

print(servers[0][0])   # web
print(servers[1][1])   # 192.168.1.20

ğŸ”¹ Practical DevOps Example ğŸ› ï¸
servers = ["web", "db", "cache"]
for server in servers:
    print(f"Checking status of {server} server...")
